		<h1 style="text-align:center">THIS IS A CHEAT SHEET</h1> 
		<h1 style="text-align:center">FOR HTML5</h1> 
      <h1>All related to text</h1>
	  
	<section>
	  <h2>Formating</h2>
	  
	 <h3>Italic</h3>
		&ltem&gtYOUR TEXT&lt/em&gt = Italic <br>
		<b>OR</b> <br>
		&lti&gtYOUR TEXT&lt/i&gt <br>
		<b>For example:</b> <br>
		<em>(&ltem&gt)Maria(&lt/em&gt)</em> goes to the beach and get's lost.</p>
		
		<br> 
		
		<h3>Bold</h3>
        &ltstrong&gtYOUR TEXT&lt/strong&gt = Bold <br> 
		<b>OR</b> <br>
		&ltb&gtYOUR TEXT&lt/b&gt <br>
		<b>For example:</b> <br>
		<b>(&ltstrong&gt)Maria(&lt/strong&gt)</b> goes to the beach and get's lost.</p>
		<br>	
	</section>
	
	<h2>Colors!</h2>
	
	<blockquote><p style="color :green;">For making texts colored you will need to put<br>
	some code inside the &ltp&gt or the &lth1&gt</p> <br>
	This is easier shown in some code: <br>
	
	<p>&ltp	 style="color :green;">Hello World&lt/p&gt will output:
	
	<p style="color :green;">Hello World</p>

	</blockquote>
	<br>
	<section>	
	 <h2>Spacing</h2>
	  
	  <h3>Next Line</h3>
		&ltbr&gtYOUR TEXT = Next line <b>(No Spacing!!!)</b> <br>
		<b>For example:</b> <br>
		Maria goes to the beach (&ltbr&gt) <br>and get's lost.</p>
		
		&ltp&gtYOUR TEXT&ltp&gt = Next line <b>(With Spacing!!!)</b> <br>
		<b>For example:</b> <br>
		<p>(&ltp&gt)Thingy(&lt/p&gt) </p>
		Another Thingy <br>
		<br>
	</section>
	<section>
	<h2>Headers</h2>
	 
	 For headers you can use: &lth1&gt, &lth2&gt, &lth3&gt, &lth4&gt, ... <br>
	 <b>This goes only only until &lth6&gt, at &lth7&gt it appears as normal text!!!</b> <br>
	 <b>For example:</b> <br>
	 <h1 style="color :black;">(&lth1&gt)Header(&lt/h1&gt)</h1> <br>
	 <h2 style="color :black;">(&lth2&gt)Header(&lth2&gt) </h2> 
	 <br>
	</section>
	
	<section>
	<h2>Lists</h2>
	
	There are 3 types of lists: 
	<ul>
	<li>Ordered lists (noted with &ltol&gt)</li> 
	<li>Unordered lists (noted with: &ltul&gt)</li>
	<li>Definition lists (noted with: &ltdl&gt)</li>
	</ul>
	
	<h3>Ordered and Unordered lists</h3>
	After you start a list (with &ltol&gt or &ltul&gt) you will include every <br>
	item between &ltli&gt and &lt/li&gt ("li" stands for list item). After this, <br>
	close the list with &lt/ol&gt or &lt/ul&gt.
	
	<h3>Definition lists</h3>
	After opening the list (with &ltdl&gt) you will put the item you want between <br>
	&ltdt&gt and &lt/dt&gt. Giving it a definition is as easy as puting the text <br>
	(or whatever else you want to put as definition) in the line imediatly after the item code <br>
	and between &ltdd&gt and &lt/dd&gt.
	
	
	
	<section>
	<h2>Other things to keep in mind.</h2>
	
	Some other things to keep in mind are: <br>
	<blockquote><dl>
	<dt>-sections (&ltsection&gtYOUR CODE&lt/section&gt)</dt>
	<dd> makes no diference visually, but helps with search engines.</dd>
	<dt>-articles (&ltarticle&gtYOUR CODE&lt/article&gt) </dt>
	<dd> makes no diference visually, but helps with screen-readears, search engines and for home assistants. </dd>
	<dt>-aside (&ltaside&gtYOUR CODE&lt/aside&gt) </dt>
	<dd> makes no diference visually, but tells screen-readears, search engines and home assistants that that information is not so important. </dd> </blockquote>
	<br>
	also 
	<br>
	<blockquote></dl>
	<dl>
	<dt>-block quotas (&ltblockquote&gtYOUR CODE&lt/blockquote&gt)</dt>
	<dd> this makes the text appear with more space by the wall, like you see in this lists.</dd></blockquote>
	</section>
